## Steps to Reproduce

* Run a 'New Flutter Project' wizard in AS.
* Select 'generate sample content' with 'RaisedButton'

Expected: a new project is created.
Actual: an error in the log
```
Error creating project
Download failed.
URL: https://master-docs-flutter-io.firebaseapp.com/snippets/material.RaisedButton.dart
Error: 404 Not Found
```

comment_data.body: Hi @akireyev.  Thanks for the report.  It looks like you have a fairly old Flutter SDK.  Could you update and try again?

Same result with
[âˆš] Flutter (Channel beta, v1.2.1, on Microsoft Windows [Version 10.0.17134.619], locale en-US)
    â€¢ Flutter version 1.2.1 at ...
    â€¢ Framework revision 8661d8aecd (2 weeks ago), 2019-02-14 19:19:53 -0800
    â€¢ Engine revision 3757390fa4
    â€¢ Dart version 2.1.2 (build 2.1.2-dev.0.0 0a7dcf17eb)
Thanks for confirming @akireyev.  We'll take a look. ðŸ‘

Sure enough, it repros from the command-line too.

It looks like the sample ids in https://docs.flutter.io/snippets/index.json aren't valid anymore?

```
[~/src/tmp] $ flutter create --sample=material.Scaffold .
Download failed.
URL: https://master-docs.flutter.io/snippets/material.Scaffold.dart
Error: 404 Not Found
```

cc @gspencergoog @DanTup

The master version of that file has numbers suffixed into the IDs:

https://master-docs.flutter.io/snippets/index.json

So the issue here is that the IDEs don't know which host `flutter create` is going to use (I think we both just assumed the stable host is fine, and there wouldn't be breaking changes). The logic Flutter uses is checking which channel it's on, though it feels a bit clunky for the editor to start checking that.

Maybe we could make a `flutter create --list` so that IDEs can get the same JSON that matches what `flutter create` supports? It can just fetch the JSON and spit it out, but use the same internal logic for checking the hostname to avoid it leaking out?

> I recall we discussed something like this at the outset (motivated by just this kind of worry).

I think there are actually two similar issues:

1. The users Flutter version being out-of-sync with the latest stable (which means the line numbers etc. may be incorrect)
2. The editor being out-of-sync with which hostname flutter tools will use

Having something like `flutter create --list` fixes the second one (breaking changes between stable/master won't cause issues like this), though sadly not the first one.

> Having something like flutter create --list fixes the second one (breaking changes between stable/master won't cause issues like this), though sadly not the first one.

Could the output be structured so as to contain that data too?  (Maybe if `--machine` is passed in too.)

Regardless, this is looking to be more of a `flutter_tools` issue.  In which case, should we move this over to the Flutter repo?

> Could the output be structured so as to contain that data too?

Which data? If you mean the line numbers etc., they'd still potentially be wrong, because they come from the web, not from the local SDK. Bundling them inside the SDK would fix this, but from previous discussions I think may be complicated (we'd need to move snippet generation from docs to Flutter?).

> this is looking to be more of a `flutter_tools` issue

Yeah, I think so. I don't think editors should need to know about (or duplicate) the internal logic used to pick the hostname, so I think a fix should come from `flutter_tools` and then the editors updated as required.

Sure, if checking the channel isn't something you can do easily, then it makes sense to ask the flutter command to give you the JSON index.  It could just as easily give you the channel, but I agree that it doesn't make sense to duplicate the logic.

I did change the naming scheme for the snippets, but I didn't think that would affect anything because the new names (with the snippet indices) appear in the JSON index. I had to add an index, since there can be multiple examples tied to a single dartdoc location. I still think it shouldn't affect anything as long as you're fetching the right JSON data.

> I still think it shouldn't affect anything as long as you're fetching the right JSON data.

Yep, that's right. We're not fetching the right data because we didn't duplicate the logic for the hostname, so if you're on `master` there's a mismatch.

Moving to something like `flutter create --list` makes the fact that it goes to the server an implementation detail that the editors no longer care about (at least, when talking to a new SDK that supports it) which feels nicer. It also makes it easier to change this (eg. if we embedded them in the SDK) in future.

@pq I suspect you have a fancy way to move issues (there's a bot? I don't know how it works), so I'll leave that to you.
This issue was moved to flutter/flutter#28896
